! conclusion:
  When a bound depends on a free parameter, choose the parameter value that gives the best result.

  + context: You have established a bound or inequality that contains a free parameter
    (epsilon, delta, t, lambda) and want the sharpest possible conclusion.
  + IF:
      The bound is valid for all (or a range of) parameter values, and different choices
      yield different strengths of conclusion.

  + HOWEVER:
      The optimisation may be analytically intractable. In that case, a sub-optimal but
      explicit choice (often guided by dimensional analysis or balancing terms) is better
      than an opaque optimal one.

  + THEN:
      Differentiate (or otherwise optimise) with respect to the free parameter. If the
      optimum has a clean closed form, use it. If not, choose a value that balances the
      dominant terms ‚Äî this typically gives the right order of magnitude.

  + BECAUSE:
      This pattern is the workhorse of concentration inequalities, moment methods, and
      approximation theory. The Chernoff bound, Bernstein inequalities, and Laplace method
      all follow by introducing an exponential parameter and optimising.

